{
  "card_id": "manipulation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Manipulation",
  "aliases": [
    "Deviation",
    "deviation",
    "False Breakout",
    "false move",
    "False Move",
    "Judas Swing",
    "Liquidity Sweep",
    "market manipulation",
    "Market Manipulation",
    "Stop Raid"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A false directional move out of a consolidation range that sweeps liquidity beyond a prior high or low, then trades back into the range, confirming failure to sustain the breakout. It is the second phase of the Power of 3 (AMD) cycle, engineered by smart money to trigger stop losses and induce traders, creating liquidity for institutions.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a consolidation or accumulation range with a defined high and low, typically following an expansion phase.",
    "Price must aggressively sweep the high or low of the range (liquidity grab) without sustained displacement.",
    "Price must fail to expand or close back inside the range, confirming a false breakout.",
    "If the high is manipulated (swept and failed), expect continuation lower; if the low is manipulated, expect a reversal higher.",
    "Confirm manipulation with a change in state of delivery (close through opposing candles) or the sweep reaching into a paired point of interest (e.g., Fair Value Gap).",
    "Anchor the manipulation leg (range extreme to sweep high/low) to project standard deviation targets (-2 to -2.5, -4 to -4.5) for the distribution phase.",
    "Price sweeps a known liquidity pool (e.g., equal highs/lows, trendlines, session highs/lows, support/resistance levels) and then quickly reverses.",
    "After the sweep, price often consolidates in a range near a point of interest, showing absorption of orders before breaking out in the intended direction.",
    "The manipulation occurs within the context of a clear overall market structure (higher highs/higher lows or lower highs/lower lows), indicating the trend direction.",
    "A breakout (initiation) in the direction opposite to the sweep confirms smart money activity and the true direction.",
    "The move is designed to trap retail traders by triggering stops at obvious levels before reversing."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Manipulation defines entry timing and bias within consolidation phases. Traders anticipate which side of the range will be swept to determine direction: a swept high into a fair value gap signals short opportunities (continuation lower); a swept low signals long opportunities (reversal higher). After a sweep is confirmed by a change in state of delivery, entry is taken on a retest of the resulting order block or fair value gap, with stops placed above/below the manipulation extreme. The manipulation leg is used to project standard deviation targets (-2 to -2.5, -4 to -4.5) for distribution confluence. Alternatively, after identifying the overall trend, wait for price to sweep liquidity in the opposite direction, then enter on a pullback (mitigation) with a tight stop beyond the manipulated level, targeting the next structural swing point.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering trades immediately after an expansion move instead of waiting for a manipulation/consolidation phase to develop.",
    "Entering on the initial sweep before a change in state of delivery confirms the move as manipulation rather than a real breakout.",
    "Confusing a manipulation sweep with a genuine breakout, leading to chasing the false move or misinterpreting a true displacement.",
    "Failing to pair the manipulation with a point of interest (e.g., Fair Value Gap), resulting in invalid setups.",
    "Taking entries outside of premium/discount zones (e.g., shorts in discount, longs in premium).",
    "Entering trades at key levels or liquidity pools without waiting for a liquidity sweep and market structure confirmation.",
    "Acting on aggressive moves (e.g., session open) or liquidity areas without waiting for the trend's directional bias and reversal signal.",
    "Placing stop losses too close to obvious highs/lows, leading to being stopped out by manipulation."
  ],
